n1_suicidal.title: You are experiencing suicidal thoughts, or have experienced suicidal thoughts at any time within the past six months.
n1_suicidal.subtitle: Research indicates that social anxiety treatment is most effective when tackled as your primary focus, which may be difficult when experiencing these thoughts.  First and foremost, we care that you get the best care available for this. We recommend that you see a therapist or call the National Lifeline (800-273-TALK).

n2_racing_thoughts.title: If, within the past six months, you’ve experienced any of the following symptoms over an extended period of time: racing thoughts, impulsive behavior, a decreased need for sleep, or mania.
n2_racing_thoughts.subtitle: If you are experiencing or have recently experienced any of these symptoms, we recommend that you consult with a mental health professional about appropriate treatment options.

n3_hear_things.title: If, at any time within the past six months, you’ve felt as if your thoughts were being controlled by someone/something other than yourself, or that you were able to see or hear things that others could not.
n3_hear_things.subtitle: If you are experiencing or have recently experienced any of these symptoms, we recommend that you consult with a mental health professional about appropriate treatment options.

n4_eating_disorder.title: If you are currently experiencing symptoms of an eating disorder, including the desire or tendency to binge eat, restrict food intake, engage in purging behaviors and/or compulsively engage in other behaviors to prevent weight gain.
n4_eating_disorder.subtitle: If you are experiencing or have recently experienced any of these symptoms, we recommend that you consult with a mental health professional about appropriate treatment options.

n5_trauma.title: You have suffered from a traumatic event that you re-experience.
n5_trauma.subtitle: This may include distressing thoughts or dreams about the event, and/or feeling as if the event is recurring. Having these symptoms does not mean that you have post-traumatic stress disorder, or PTSD, but it does suggest that you may be at risk for PTSD. In cases where someone has both PTSD and social anxiety, research indicates that it is best to work on the PTSD first before completing CBT for social anxiety. If you have any of the symptoms listed above, we recommend you see a qualified mental health professional  before working on your social anxiety.

n6_medication.title: You take anxiety, depression, or insomnia medication and have not been on a stable dosage for more than 4 weeks.
n6_medication.subtitle: If you take medication for anxiety, depression, or insomnia, researchers believe it is best for you to be on a stable dosage before and during CBT for social anxiety. This is for two reasons: first, having a stable medication dosage will help you recognize the gains that come from CBT vs. the medication; and, second, it can be hard to stick with a course of CBT while managing the mental and physical effects of a change in medication. If you believe your medication change may create either of these challenges, we recommend you consider waiting until your medications have stabilized before beginning the AbleTo program.

n7_drugs.title: You cannot avoid the use of alcohol or drugs in conjunction with AbleTo activities, or are concerned that exposure to stressful situations may interfere with substance use treatment or recovery.
n7_drugs.subtitle: A crucial part of CBT is experiencing intense levels of anxiety, and learning that you can cope with those experiences on your own, and that they will naturally subside. Using alcohol or drugs during activities can interfere with that process. In addition, if you believe that exposure to stress may affect your ability to abstain from substance use, AbleTo may not be right for you at this time.

n4_medication.title: If you take medication for anxiety on an as-needed basis.
n4_medication.subtitle: A crucial part of CBT for anxiety is experiencing anxiety and learning that the physical symptoms that accompany it will subside, and most importantly, that you can cope with the experience. Taking anxiety medication on an as-needed basis can interfere with that process, as people often attribute their ability to deal with a stressful situation as resulting from taking the medication. This will lessen the benefit of engaging in a course of challenge in the course of CBT. If you take medication such as beta-blockers or benzodiazepines on an as needed basis to help you overcome your anxiety in social situations, you may want to discuss with your prescribing healthcare provider how that would impact your potential progress in this program. If you are considering discontinuing or changing your medication, it is very important to discuss with your provider how this would impact not only your social anxiety, but other difficulties you may be experiencing. Please note that any changes you may consider making to your medication(s) should be discussed with your healthcare provider(s)

faqs.content: AbleTo provides virtual therapy and emotional support programs that are based on leading research and clinical standards, as applicable. Our network of highly trained and experienced coaches and licensed therapists have delivered more than 1 million sessions over phone and video in the last 10 years to help people reach their goals and feel better.
faqs.title: What is AbleTo?

faqs.content: AbleTo's programs are based on a type of therapy that focuses on how your thoughts, feelings, and actions are all connected. This is called Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT). Over 8 weeks, we'll help you understand those connections, change unhelpful patterns of thoughts and actions, and build skills you can use for life to feel better. Our programs are {{#a}}[proven to reduce depression, stress, and anxiety](https://ableto.com/our-impact/){{/a}}, and can help you manage things that matter to you, from day-to-day concerns to coping with health conditions like diabetes, heart disease, and more.
faqs.title: How does AbleTo work?

faqs.content: AbleTo uses highly trained licensed therapists, behavioral coaches, and motivational coaches from across the country. We'll help you find a type of provider for your needs and goals and you'll work with them throughout your program. All of our therapists and coaches receive full and ongoing training to deliver AbleTo's {{#a}}[proven programs](https://ableto.com/our-impact/){{/a}}* that can be tailored to all backgrounds and identities.
faqs.title: Who will I work with?

faqs.content:
There's {{#a}}[a large amount of evidence](https://ableto.com/our-impact/){{/a}} that shows focused care delivered over a certain time period, like AbleTo's clinically-based 8-week programs, can not only provide short-term positive results, but can also be enough time to learn life skills that can be used in the future to help you feel better.

At the end of your program, you can always talk to your therapist or coach about ways to get more support if you want it.

Our programs are {{#a}}[proven to reduce depression, stress, and anxiety](https://ableto.com/our-impact/){{/a}}, and can help you manage things that matter to you, from day-to-day concerns to coping with health conditions like diabetes, heart disease, and more.
faqs.title: How does AbleTo work?

faqs.content: AbleTo uses highly trained licensed therapists, behavioral coaches, and motivational coaches from across the country. We'll help you find a type of provider for your needs and goals and you'll work with them throughout your program. All of our therapists and coaches receive full and ongoing training to deliver AbleTo's {{#a}}[proven programs](https://ableto.com/our-impact/){{/a}}* that can be tailored to all backgrounds and identities.
faqs.title: Who will I work with?

faqs.content:
There's {{#a}}[a large amount of evidence](https://ableto.com/our-impact/){{/a}} that shows focused care delivered over a certain time period, like AbleTo's clinically-based 8-week programs, can not only provide short-term positive results, but can also be enough time to learn life skills that can be used in the future to help you feel better.

At the end of your program, you can always talk to your therapist or coach about ways to get more support if you want it.
faqs.title: Why is the program 8 weeks of sessions?

content_sections: {{#header3}}AbleTo Cookie Policy{{/header3}} {{#p}}We ask that you read this cookie policy carefully as it contains important information on our use of cookies or similar technologies on our website. This policy should be read together with our Privacy Notice, which set out how and why we collect, store, use and share personal information generally, as well as your rights in relation to your personal information and details of how to contact us and supervisory authorities in the event that you have a complaint.{{/p}} {{#p}}Even if you do not register with or provide any Personal Information to AbleTo, we will automatically collect certain information through cookies and similar technologies, as described below (“Automatically Collected Information”).  We will treat such information as Personal Information.{{/p}}

{{#header4}}Cookies and Web Beacons{{/header4}} {{#p}}We collect Automatically Collected Information about your use of the Services and your use of other web sites through the use of Cookies and Web Beacons. “Cookies” are small data files that are stored on the hard drive of the computer you use to view a web site. Every computer that accesses the Services is assigned a different cookie by AbleTo.{{/p}} {{#p}}“Web Beacons” are graphic image files imbedded in a web page typically used to monitor activity on a web page and send back to its home server (which can belong to the host site, a network advertiser or some other third party) information from your browser, such as the IP address, the URL of the page on which the beacon is located, the type browser that is accessing the site and the ID number of any Cookies on your computer previously placed by that server.{{/p}} {{#p}}Through Cookies we place on your browser or device, we may collect information about your activity when you use the Services. Just like any other usage information we collect, this information allows us to improve the Services, customize your online experience and authenticate your account, among other things. You can set your browser not to accept cookies and the websites below tell you how to remove cookies from your browser. However, some of our website features may not function as a result.{{/p}} {{#p}}Third parties under contract with AbleTo may use Cookies or Web Beacons to collect Automatically Collected Information about your usage of the Services on our behalf and pursuant to our instructions.{{/p}} {{#p}}You may select which cookies to allow, block or delete (in whole or in part) through the specific functions of your browser. However, if all or some of the cookies are disabled, the website may not be available or may not work properly and you may be forced to change or manually enter some information or preferences each time you visit the website. For more information on how to set preferences on the use of cookies through your browser, click the appropriate link:{{/p}} $t(cookies:cookieLinks)

We use this number in a manner similar to our use of Cookies. Unlike Cookies, the number is assigned to your installation of the App itself and not a browser. If you do not want us to use the number for the purposes for which we use Cookies, please do not use our App.{{/p}}
